This dressing came out blah for me - I thought it lacked the zing of a good vinaigrette. I did use valencia oranges from my yard, though, which tend to be sweeter rather than on the tart side. Based on the previous reviews, I'll try it again with different oranges. I served the dressing with a baby spinach/mixed green salad with dried cranberries, toasted almonds and goat cheese.

Rating: 3
This was delicious. I didn't have lemons, so used lime juice. I think I would like it better with lemon juice. I also added 2 tablespoons mango preserves.

Rating: 4
My modified version was excellent, receiving rave reviews from my diners. Like the previous reviewer, I used cumin powder, rather than seeds, and I added dijon mustard for additional flavor. Also: I used about 1/2 the oil and substituted walnut oil for vegetable oil (produced a lighter dressing and was very tasty). Finally, I used lemon, instead of limes (didn't have any limes on hand), and I increased the amount of juice to add more tang. All in all, the recipe survived my modifications and was appreciated by all. This is an easy (and obviously) versatile recipe. It will now be a staple in my kitchen.

Rating: 4
Excellent! I also did not have cumin seed on hand,so I used ground cumin. The only change was to add about 1 teaspoon Dijon mustard for a little zip. I used the dressing on a salad of endive, parsley, spinach with oranges and dried cranberries.

